### Abstract

Eco-Town programs that pioneered Japan’s circular society development represent early practices of the circular economy (CE) grounded in Industry–Urban Symbiosis (IUS). While they advanced resource circulation and environmental impact reduction, they also revealed ecosystem-level challenges, including weak firm engagement, unstable recycled material supply, fragile markets, and misalignment between technological innovation and institutional arrangements. These issues largely stem from an IUS perspective that prioritized material and energy flows while overlooking knowledge flows and inter-actor relationships essential for value co-creation. In response, this study examines how such knowledge flows underpin regional Circular Service Ecosystems (CSEs), drawing on a service ecosystem perspective and the knowledge-based view. Using a qualitative case study of two SMEs in a national eco-industrial park in Jiangsu Province, China, based on factory observations and focus group interviews with firm leaders and downstream partners, it proposes a hypothetical framework showing how multi-actor knowledge integration supports firm engagement, institutional reconfiguration, and sustained CE practices.

